        <p data-uuid="4f7a7ebaf8b849a38c12b8b607953462">Settlers in New England built a diverse economy based on shipping, fishing, farming, and manufacturing. Puritan families valued education and built schools for their children. Politics and religion were closely connected, with only church members allowed to vote or hold office. The center of politics was the town meeting, where people met to discuss local issues. Conflict over religious beliefs led Puritan leaders to banish people like Anne Hutchinson and Roger Williams from Massachusetts.</p>
        <h3 data-uuid="8827b1a860744cf5b2e8c6fec76474e5">The Middle Colonies</h3>
        <p data-uuid="9ab62d669276473facf0b6a5dfb69939">The middle colonies included New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Delaware. They combined qualities of the New England and southern colonies. Like New England, they had many towns and were centers of trade with Britain and the West Indies. Like the southern colonies, the middle colonies grew large amounts of crops, mainly wheat, barley, and oats. Indentured servants and, to a lesser degree, slaves did much of the labor.</p>
